Gulf of Maine Seasonal Sea Surface Temperature Update

Seasonal Patterns in Sea Surface Temperatures

Author

Adam Kemberling

Published

April 4, 2023

About the Updates:

Over the past decade, scientists at the Gulf of Maine Research Institute have led a body of research that highlights the rapid pace of warming in the Gulf of Maine. To keep you informed, we share seasonal updates about conditions in the Gulf of Maine.

New in 2023: Moving the Climatological Reference

This yearâs reporting will now be done using a new 30-year climatological reference period, a transition from to a 1991-2020 climate baseline. This change is in accordance with the standards set by international science community, following the U.S. âClimate Normalsâ used by organizations like the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Association and the World Meteorological Organization.

Learn more about how scientists study climate, and the details of this transition, in our marine heatwaves technical report.

Note About the Data: The figures in this report are created using remotely-sensed satellite data as part of publicly funded research efforts. Satellite SST data was obtained from NOAAâs National Center for Environmental Information (NCEI), with all maps and figures displaying NOAAâs Optimum Interpolation Sea Surface Temperature Data.

Note on Preliminary Data: This dataset has a 2-week latency period, during which values may change due to quality control measures. Any data within 14 days of the publishing date may be subject to change.

The Gulf of Maine Region

For analyses like these, it is important to be clear about the spatial extent that âdefinesâ the Gulf of Maine (FigureÂ 1), as different borders could produce different results. The spatial domain we use as the âGulf of Maineâ is displayed below. This area is consistent with previous reports and publications GMRI has produced.

Season Highlights

For this seasonal report we present an analysis of SST for winter (December 1st - February 28th) for the year 2023. This season the average SST for the Gulf of Maine was 47.64Â°F, making it the new hottest winter on record for the period of 1982-2023 â the period over which the satellite data used are available. This seasonal average temperature is 3.58Â°F above the long-term (1991-2020) winter average of 44.06Â°F.

Weekly Temperatures

In the below table (TableÂ 1), we highlight how the SST for each week this winter compares to a 30-year baseline period (i.e., climatological averages from 1991 through 2020).

The observed SST, long-term average SST, and SST anomalies (i.e., departures from the long-term average SST) are shown. SSTs in the winter typically begin to slowly level out, before reaching their lowest around March. This pattern is evident this Winter as expected, , with anomalies cresting over three periods within the course of the season. Departures from the long-term average hovered around 3Â°F above normal with a few weeks punctuated by anomalies in excess of 5Â°F, once in December, then again at the end of January, and again in mid-February.

Seasonal Trends and Anomalies in Context

The Gulf of Maine is an area of particular interest to the scientific community because of the remarkable rate of warming it has experienced in recent years coupled with its importance as a major driver for the regional economy.

When looking at average winter temperatures from the beginning of the satellite record in 1982, there is a clear long-term increase, with SSTâs warming at a rate of 0.81Â°F per decade. This rate of warming is ~4x the rate that global ocean temperatures are warming during these same months, a rate of 0.21Â°F per decade.

The unprecedented levels of warmth over the past decade or so are consistent with what researchers believe has been a distinct regime shift in terms of the major influences on SSTs in the Gulf of Maine. The drivers of this (e.g., a potential weakening of the Atlantic Meridional Overturning Circulation and widening of the Gulf Stream) have been well-documented in the peer-reviewed literature, including through research by GMRI scientists.

How Does 2023 Compare?

2023 is the new warmest winter season observed in the Gulf of Maine during the 41 years we have satellite data to analyze. The top 5 warmest winter seasons have all occurred in the last decade.

Marine Heatwave Conditions

The most commonly used definition of a âmarine heatwaveâ (MHW) is when daily average SSTâs exceed the 90th percentile of a climatological (i.e., 30-year) average for at least 5 consecutive days. Gaps of 2 days or less in this threshold do not constitute a break in the MHW event.

Using this broadly accepted definition, the Gulf of Maine has experienced MHW conditions for 82.22% of winter 2023. A 16 day period over the New-Yearâs transition (Dec 27th - January 11th) were the only dates where SST was below the threshold for a MHW.

Presenting SST conditions in terms of anomalies (FigureÂ 4) as opposed to absolute values (FigureÂ 3) illustrates in greater detail the magnitude of MHW conditions throughout the winter. The most extreme anomalies occurred in December, with temperatures spiking above 5`Â°F above the climatological average. Temperatures fell closer to the climate norm over the end of December, before rising to the +3 to +4Â°F range for the second half of January and through February.

Heatmap of Temperature Anomalies and Heatwave Events

Looking at the full record of daily SST anomalies in the Gulf of Maine (FigureÂ 5), the distinct thermal regime shift beginning around 2010 is evident. Indeed, since 2012, the Gulf of Maine has experienced far more persistent MHW conditions (indicated by solid black lines) than at any other point in the satellite record.

Spatial Distribution of Seasonal Anomalies

From a spatial perspective, the Gulf of Maine and surrounding areas experienced above average SSTâs for much of the region during winter 2023, but the warmest patches were to the south and east of Georges Bank, mostly outside the domain analyzed in preceding sections. The highest seasonally averaged anomaly of any location above was 11.41Â°F.

Monthly Temperature Anomalies

Average monthly SST anomalies are shown in FigureÂ 8. The warmest anomalies were in December and concentrated to two pockets just south and to the south east of the domain studied in this analysis. During January a band of cold-water anomalies emerged to the southeast of these patches, but by February the areas just south and east of Georges Bank had spiked again. Monthly-averaged SST anomalies in the Gulf of Maine and the surrounding areas reached > 8Â°F warmer than during our climate reference period (1991-2020).
